1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,240
We have already covered how multi-head attention works in a transformer.

2

00:00:04,240  -->  00:00:07,820
Now we will cover how to implement a transformer's block.

3

00:00:07,820  -->  00:00:10,500
When we pass a prompt to a model,

4

00:00:10,500  -->  00:00:14,800
we convert each input token into an embedding vector,

5

00:00:14,800  -->  00:00:19,395
and then pass these vectors to multi-head attention block.

6

00:00:19,395  -->  00:00:22,380
The output of the multi-head attention then goes to

7

00:00:22,380  -->  00:00:26,090
the feed-forward network layer and the output

8

00:00:26,090  -->  00:00:30,210
of this layer will be sent further to the next transformer block.

9

00:00:30,210  -->  00:00:32,530
If you recall in one of the previous videos,

10

00:00:32,530  -->  00:00:39,305
we discussed that a transformer model consists of multiple such blocks chained together.

11

00:00:39,305  -->  00:00:41,810
Once we have this block implemented,

12

00:00:41,810  -->  00:00:44,750
we will be almost done with the model implementation.

13

00:00:44,750  -->  00:00:48,680
Let's now take a look at what happens in the feed-forward layer.

14

00:00:48,680  -->  00:00:52,810
The feed-forward layer is applied to each embedding vector individually.

15

00:00:52,810  -->  00:00:56,580
Each embedding vector is passed to a linear layer with

16

00:00:56,580  -->  00:01:00,730
an output size that is four times larger than the input size.

17

00:01:00,730  -->  00:01:03,930
To add non linearity to these transformations,

18

00:01:03,930  -->  00:01:09,320
we will also apply the GELU activation function which we'll cover in a minute.

19

00:01:09,320  -->  00:01:11,620
We then take this output and shrink

20

00:01:11,620  -->  00:01:14,980
the output factor down to the original embedding size.

21

00:01:14,980  -->  00:01:20,300
Now, let's also briefly talk about the GELU activation function that we will use.

22

00:01:20,300  -->  00:01:23,710
It is similar to the ReLU activation function.

23

00:01:23,710  -->  00:01:27,250
Here is a chart of the GELU activation function.

24

00:01:27,250  -->  00:01:31,740
For comparison, here is a chart of the ReLU activation function.

25

00:01:31,740  -->  00:01:38,100
As you can see, the GELU function has a smooth shape compared to the ReLU's sharp corner,

26

00:01:38,100  -->  00:01:41,980
and this smooth shape allows to get better training results.

27

00:01:41,980  -->  00:01:45,600
This is a gist of how a transformer block is organized,

28

00:01:45,600  -->  00:01:48,530
but there are a few more details that we need to cover.

29

00:01:48,530  -->  00:01:52,000
First, there are two residual connections in this block.

30

00:01:52,000  -->  00:01:55,800
A residual connection is when we take an input to a certain block,

31

00:01:55,800  -->  00:02:01,000
and we then add it to the out-put of the block before we pass the result forward.

32

00:02:01,000  -->  00:02:02,800
Residual connections help with

33

00:02:02,800  -->  00:02:06,580
the vanishing gradient problem that we've briefly covered before.

34

00:02:06,580  -->  00:02:08,340
Just to remind you,

35

00:02:08,340  -->  00:02:10,880
the vanishing gradient is the issue when

36

00:02:10,880  -->  00:02:14,300
the gradient becomes very small in deep networks.

37

00:02:14,300  -->  00:02:18,960
Using residual connections makes training deep neural network more efficient.

38

00:02:18,960  -->  00:02:21,200
In addition to residual connections,

39

00:02:21,200  -->  00:02:23,580
we have a few more extra components.

40

00:02:23,580  -->  00:02:29,250
These include the layer normalization and the dropout layer.

41

00:02:29,250  -->  00:02:32,420
We've already covered what is a dropout layer.

42

00:02:32,420  -->  00:02:37,025
Now let's also briefly cover what is a layer normalization.

43

00:02:37,025  -->  00:02:40,160
The layer normalization scales the output of

44

00:02:40,160  -->  00:02:45,960
one layer so that the mean or average of the output values become zero,

45

00:02:45,960  -->  00:02:48,500
and variance becomes equal to one.

46

00:02:48,500  -->  00:02:52,735
Using layer normalization allows us to achieve faster training.

47

00:02:52,735  -->  00:02:55,770
This layer is also implemented in Pytorch,

48

00:02:55,770  -->  00:02:59,290
and we will use a type called layer norm for this.

49

00:02:59,290  -->  00:03:01,450
This is it, just to recap,

50

00:03:01,450  -->  00:03:05,150
every layer or block of a transformer model receives

51

00:03:05,150  -->  00:03:10,345
an input that goes through multi-head attention and the feed-forward network.

52

00:03:10,345  -->  00:03:13,070
Then to improve the training results,

53

00:03:13,070  -->  00:03:15,770
we also use layer normalization,

54

00:03:15,770  -->  00:03:18,670
dropout, and residual connections.

55

00:03:18,670  -->  00:03:21,010
Now, once we've covered how it works,

56

00:03:21,010  -->  00:03:24,570
let's go and implement it for our model.
